A Republican strategy to hamper Obama's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and claims that voter fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only found 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And along that same line, a majority of American governments enacted, beginning in 2009, new laws that made the process of registering or voting difficult.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, during 2011 180 bills were introduced restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID, plus proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 election, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
So the Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a state government agency.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often getting the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions therefore disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
Moreover, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed certain laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on the same day as the ballot in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to help voters who wished to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 have led to a fall in the rate of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored shortening the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33% of the voters who cast ballots in advance were African-American, while the latter represented no more than 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, it was exactly the same.
These represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent no more than 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have been vehemently opposed to passing laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damage was partially contained.
For example, only 16 of 34 states passed the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have passed such laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this respect, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: To be tested or not?
The PSA test sometimes produces false negative or even false positive results, after which it is decided to carry out unnecessary medical interventions.
It is more than enough to make men, already reluctant, doubt whether or not they should be tested.
To take the test or not?
We've asked two specialists for advice.
Studies in the United States have found a high rate of infection among the sample groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and make firm recommendations.
The European study showed some difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who had not.
The study, which followed up at 12 years of age, also showed that there is a 30 to 40% chance of metastasis if the screening test has not been carried out.
I recommend testing at age 50, or at age 40 if your father has had prostate cancer.
African-American men have a higher risk index.
The key is to make a good decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive cancers and other cancers that are indolent.
It is really necessary to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his cancer. He should be offered all possible options and not necessarily treat prostate cancers that do not threaten life in the long term, in which case active surveillance of the disease should be preferred.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer go untreated, since the cancer is neither aggressive nor life-threatening.
Instead, we suggest active surveillance of the disease and, if it progresses, offer treatment.
We increasingly determine precise criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated.
I recommend you get tested anyway.
But it is important that you talk to your doctor about whether you should get tested.
Movember has created, in collaboration with the International Urological Society, a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of the PSA test.
