Preventing the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for cancer.
Despite the progress of research, adopting healthy lifestyle habits remains the best way to reduce the risk of developing the disease.
We estimate that if everyone ate right and got enough exercise, we could prevent 30 percent of cancers.
"If no one smoked, that rate would rise to at least 50 percent", points out André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
Instead, we estimate that about 10 percent of cancers are hereditary.
Many others remain totally unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, the fight against smoking remains a priority despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Tobacco is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for other types of cancer.
It is extremely damaging to people's health.
"Today, there are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec", said spokesman André Beaulieu.
Here's a hopeful fact: 10 years after quitting, the risk of dying from cancer is cut in half.
Weight
Obesity and obesity also contribute to the onset of the disease, according to the SCC.
They increase the risk of breast, colon and rectal, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancers.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against breast cancer", they add.
The food
The agency also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
In large amounts, they escalate the risk of developing colorectal cancer.
Carcutery products should also be avoided.
Preserving meat for smoking, drying or salting can cause the formation of carcinogens.
"They can damage the cells of the body and lead to the development of cancer", they explain.
