Mr Beaulieu also stresses the importance of discussing your concerns and family history with your doctor.
"Doing the screening test doesn't cause cancer".
The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a great deal of commotion last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in effect, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what's more, it's the particle that the Standard Model predicted would exist: our best or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has yet to be empirically observed.
But it's not entirely clear to physicists that it's the Higgs.
We know for sure that there is a new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data are still missing to be completely certain.
Anyway, we're assuming that it's the Higgs, because the chances of getting it wrong seem slim.
There is, in this great world, a general and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule, and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And then there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure at Berkeley Labs, which is, by the way, extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", which are the forces that nature's great forces propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I should stress here, are not the exotic beasts we might believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily mundane boson - the photon, or "light particle", that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that particular environment - much like throwing a stone into a pond.
From this "disorder" comes an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except that it's another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to activate it, you have to reach extremely high energies, a little like a frozen pond where only a thick rock can slide across the surface.
So an immense particle accelerator like the one at CERN (the great hadron collider is a 27 km ring!) is needed to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick by itself to a refrigerator door.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way) don't.
What can all this research 'bring' to the table?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between the observations and predictions of the MS.
Many, on the other hand, are eager to meet, for the slightest difference could open the door to a "new physics" that fills certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has huge flaws, such as not proposing any explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (more oops!).
But we haven't found such differences at CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of such research on our daily lives is difficult to predict, but we do not think we are wrong to say that it will not have any.
So, look, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser in the laboratory had no idea what a revolution their work would bring about.
They were able to see the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, has said, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Can you imagine?
And, in addition, applications can also come from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light-capturing device in 1969 in the course of his research in optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this sensor now serves as the "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That doesn't mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC are necessarily going to transform our lives, but you never know...
Palliative care, the best way to die is to...
In its Die with Dignity Commission, Quebec recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should resume soon while a bill is being prepared.
Now, within that essential domain, there is still much to be done.
Le Devoir has tried to see it up close.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The cancer of the prostate that was destroying him had given him a two-year break.
"I had been given five years to live, but I've been like this for seven", he relates, making a pass, lying on his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for this", he continues.
The disease has taken its toll on him: a tremendous weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating alone.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he resignedly accepts help to eat.
Brave, he even smiles, talks to strangers who pay attention, bring him medicines, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating", she confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for that ailment.
"In the course of our lives we learn that a man urinates standing up", relates Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois center.
To return to their childhood, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"That depends on the person's ability to accept that regression", he says.
Because, in the opinion of most people who work in palliative care, the great moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
Every patient who comes into the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Center has cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide "curative" care.
Mrs. A., 89,'s greatest fear is dying "conscious and drowned".
But the disease has made him discover his children.
"I have good children", he adds.
"I have no more desires left in this life", she says, before agreeing to be put on a mask to help her breathe.
And he expects, in the next few days, a final visit from his son who lives in Italy.
A group of volunteers offer body care and food assistance at Victor-Gadbois.
It's palliative care that's given to them when there's nothing else you can do.
To help make his death more comfortable.
In Quebec, we have one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little, since we all know that we're going to die one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the center's doctors.
Whether it's physical comfort, emotional comfort or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is offered mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, depending on the lawsuit.
Diabetics are no longer able to control their blood sugar.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer, who died during the course of the night.
This morning, your son finished his beer at the dead man's feet.
"We help both patients and their loved ones", relates Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois Center, days go by and they're never the same.
Next to a 94-year-old man enjoying his last family gathering in the yard, well-placed between his pillows as everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, wife and two children, after trying everything to survive.
"For six months now, there have always been three to five beds occupied by people under 45 years of age with cancer", worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadboisarrivent come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the end of his life, whether at home, in a hospital or in a care facility.
And several organizations, like the Victor-Gadbois Center and the Home Palliative Care Society of Grand Montreal, specialize almost exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this great relative shortage in Quebec's health care that makes many palliative care doctors fear the passage of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe has circulated to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health care system is not competent enough to ensure that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
"Recently", he relates, "I saw a patient spend 14 days in the ER in excruciating pain without any relief.
I fear that patients may want to die just because they are not receiving proper care".
And at the same time, many oncologists are stubborn with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already low when she stopped exhausting chemotherapy treatment.
"When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop the treatment, she told me that she was very sorry that I wanted to stop fighting", he relates.
"But she had told me there was nothing else to do!"
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die thank their caregivers for not answering their demands once their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
But palliative care is not all-powerful when it comes to pain management.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care in Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8 percent of cases.
At the end of life, doctors usually resort to palliative sedation, which serves to put the patient to sleep until the time of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend we don't understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved disease is going to have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
The unrelieved patients all say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want euthanasia", but "I want relief".
