With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
This is the opposite of the current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing charges between parties.
Moreover, as is often the case with technology, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency convertible to dollars, euros, etc. and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files on an equal basis.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been recorded thanks to 15,000 computers in the network.
And about a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a form of payment.
The bitcoin price, after reaching a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (the quotes are censored on the bitcoincharts.com page).
It's not impressive when compared to the world's changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) became interested in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as "credits", used to advance in a video game and which can be earned by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange, a central authority controls and handles the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously bookkeepers, verifiers, coin issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two electronic addresses in the form of e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically via a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanges of bitcoins are recorded in the public ledger, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This involves solving a mathematical challenge thrown to the computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
It is a file-sharing phase, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "catch" the new transaction and add a number before "crunching" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it's the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is split in two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
