He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Only a week ago the Head of State had given the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And for almost two years Egypt has been using a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial messes.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" and continues "betraying his word" and "trampling on the law".
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a regulation on the protection of the environment.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short time which forced the Brothers to abandon their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way of recovering popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy is wreaking havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote for him, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal was voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either vote for my text or I retain full powers", powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, the vast majority of whom are Islamists, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the meeting.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not enforce their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people were added as replacement members yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators are pleased, moreover, that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed almost at the time of the prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all the eyeballs, is still ultimately identical to the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the norms", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
