The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of the university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not scholars but university students, some of them trained in the French system", explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
"We are referring specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to rule above all this".
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers it confers on the president of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to what they were during the previous regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be banned, as human rights groups have called for.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy remains and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
Furthermore, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
The only positive thing, she said, was the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
