"At the moment, it's not so easy to fool the brain".
The topic of augmented reality, so popular among modern technology enthusiasts, is now normally perceived mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer, at its annual conference Google demonstrated a moving model and later, in November, it became known that Microsoft had also submitted an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge lab, Izadi Sharamom, it became clear that for the company's scientists, glasses were already a thing of the past.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We're dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we're also trying to push the boundaries of this interaction.
For now, humanity in its great mass has been caught in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look five to ten years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and no Xbox is sold today without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else is in the future?
- Even though Kinect has taken interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We're trying to change that, we're working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design.
We must free the world of computing to our own, to the physical, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user but also the space around him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those silly VR helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course, it can't be considered a panacea, it's still pending to resolve the privacy issue, since we don't always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of computer interaction are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for controlling devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not loose movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, gestures were captured not by the device's camera, but by a wristband that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
It's very big for now, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this soda can to you?
You'll talk and show it at the same time.
- Normally I just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at this point?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think in the near future we're going to have to work primarily on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, because they provide good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- Speaking of your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what may be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But the question is not megapixels, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this last point of view, all the current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to the algorithm designers.
So we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on the Z axis.
It's also about speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our Redmond laboratory, made a contact sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
I would find it very useful for my work to have an equivalent of such a device, but one that does not require contact so that the frames per second are more.
- And isn't it necessary to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is in fact the infrared emitter and the second the reflected signal receiver.
But the third camera is actually a simple sensor of the visible rangefinder.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or, on the contrary, increase it and increase the required number of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analog of Kinect, play with the camera location curve and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- As I recall, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not introduced its glasses to the public.
Do you not agree that, from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding a smartphone in your hands, it's not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could go from glasses to a smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, that's their strength (private things only you can see), but also their weakness: Augmented reality based on glasses won't allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any mere mortal.
There is a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile response!
My hands feel nothing!
What responses does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth might as well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
It records the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really geared to give tangibleness to these "images in the air", for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is, gives a feeling similar to what you feel if someone is blowing on your fingertips, but that feeling is still very faint.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this too a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think he feels what he seems to feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another challenge that we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that he is going to an open space, almost endlessly.
Right now, fooling the brain is not so easy, you still have to work for many years.
That's what makes working with virtual reality so appealing to researchers, that a lot of things are in a state of complete conception.
