The problems of reproduction in space with flora began to be addressed.
Experiments with plants have been carried out for half a century.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were no different from the varieties on land.
Then came the breeding of insects in orbit, small fruit flies, the drosophila.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to test how an embryo develops under weightless conditions.
The result is a normal chick.
But then the trouble starts.
"The problem is that this chick has to find support, it has to stand on its own feet and start moving", explains Vladimir Sychev, the director of the laboratory at the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IPBM) of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
Unable to find support, the chicks flipped around at random.
And after 10 hours, the newborns had a complete atrophy of instincts.
The chicks didn't react to light or sound.
And the misfortune was that after four days they just died.
"And twice we got the chicks to be born, but then we stopped because it was impossible to work there with them", comments Vladimir Sychev on the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
