NKÚ chief: Inspection of the "švarc" system has not found the guilty politician
The Czech Republic has good inspectors and quality legislation in the field of public procurement, although its implementation is lax.
This is stated by Miloslav Kala, vice president of the Supreme Control Office (NKÚ) in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect", but its application must be correct. "This is what we lack, in my opinion", describes the current situation.
The joint inspections by the Czech and German inspectors also reach similar conclusions.
As an example of incorrect practice, he mentions Petr Nečas's attitude towards the system of being autonomous only on paper, which is known as the "švarc" system.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS (Civic Democratic Party) would not harass businessmen with inspectors.
"The law must be regulated in some way and if it prohibits something, in that case, neither the president of the government can prevent the performance of the office that has the obligation to carry out such controls nor to demand obligations", Kala says.
At the meeting of the audit committee in the Congress of Deputies, you spoke of the joint project between the Czech and German teams, in which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What is it exactly?
This is a parallel control that we started to do about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation regulates how public procurement should be organised, followed by national legislation and then by practice itself.
We have combined everything and, although the control is not yet complete, we have found very interesting differences.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to introduce ever stricter rules, but that the focus should be on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually bring?
It is precisely such a common control that could help to reduce the effort we put into making laws, reducing and improving the limits, even if this does not have such a positive impact.
The economy of saving means getting a suitable thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean that the price is the lowest) to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But the fact that we are reducing the limit on the allocation of funds does not mean that we are going to achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much "paperwork", that those who want to look for flaws in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You are talking about the problems of our country with the transfer of legislation regulating the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized differently?
As far as the offices, such as the NKU, are concerned, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors), with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in their case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but as Germany has a federal organization, the Court of Auditors is even at this level.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, are checked by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for the local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to say exactly where it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
That's certainly not the case, but, again, I don't like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries which we take as a model have to face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, it wouldn't be any benefit to you to collaborate with our office, would it?
As regards the legislation in our country, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean for your Office?
The Commission has not yet taken a decision on the matter.
Since we are carrying out ex post controls, there is a certain delay to be expected.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals for the future of the European Union, including the setting up of a European network of national experts to monitor the implementation of the European Union's policies and the development of the European Union's policies.
Do you think that the passage of this law is beneficial or that it is rather a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope it will be.
The problem that can arise is that the rules "get tougher" and it becomes impossible to enforce them.
Under the previous rules, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and any law not respected in the field of public procurement was a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to tighten the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
A system of this kind will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
