The architectural studio MVRDV shows that real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "mountain of books" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there's finally something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, notes: "Also, the building is beautiful".
But I wonder what we need a library for today.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody just goes into those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town just outside Rotterdam that is hardly worth a quick visit, has the dubious honor of having risen to a record of oblivion.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture by copying the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the policy makers decided that there was only one way to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, of the Dutch architecture firm MVRDV, a master of the art of bar diagrams and responsible for buildings that are fun and cynical, took the subject with his usual serenity and attended the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around in perplexity and shrugged their shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here is my proposal for the Spijkenisse book mountain, the so-called `Boekenberg'.
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises in the planned place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of apartment and townhouses.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
Thus, the little town lacking in history, which until now had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly city hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it's a paradise of books under a cheese-pot.
True, there is an elevator that takes us right to the center of this mountain range, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, preferring to blend in with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to see, the recessed brick floor and elegant lanterns unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up, you can see the park benches, the dogs, and the boys and girls playing soccer.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"The bookshelves are usually arranged along the facade and in the middle there is a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
What we've done is we've turned the classical spatial configuration upside down and moved the reading zone from inside to outside.
The interior of the mountain is well-utilized: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention is made of the black shelves which assume the functions of wall cladding, parapet and rail at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even the most seasoned architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear of this unfamiliar material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the town of Spijkenisse.
And so one day, on a Frisian farm, we stumbled upon the right by-product from farming.
For many years, greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands have used a plastic fabric of a few millimetres thick as a base for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to four centimeters thick plates.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous, tough material that smells like a mixture of a new car and a sneaker.
After 105 steps, you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain, the reward awaits us: from the cafeteria, not only do we have a fantastic view of the city, but we can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment while maintaining the right humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology", says Trouborst.
The heating and cooling needed is obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun shines for only a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located transversely to the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there, too.
Also, the professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She calls the "Boekenberg" the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
The aim is to fill the gaps in a library which does not yet have its complete archive, which currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows your book is part of the library.
Even if it's only there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a great success in the main discipline, which in the specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The town of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
No matter how young and uneducated he may be.
Finally a starting point for forming your identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more leading role"
Germany abstained on the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather acute diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany indicated that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status at the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the special relationship that binds the country to Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to show its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from the issue of establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear stand when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, that's right.
This is because at the moment it is reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they have already started the road to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Britain.
What does a 'normal' foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy which, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, that is to say, by exports and by its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The German economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other great powers and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken on the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or from Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't give it that much importance since it's not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys a tremendous degree of understanding.
I do not think that we have had a breakthrough as drastic as in Libya.
Perhaps Germany has earned some respect for itself.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the United States has been clear in favour of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration is secretly showing a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation that is being lived here, it is obvious that the government cannot defend that position in public.
I think that the real disparity of opinion is not really as large as it is supposed to be.
If we look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policies he is developing.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States with the position of its main partners in the EU?
I think that's precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
They therefore have no possibility of being part of a higher entity, but must drive things from their own position.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, whether simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a very funny subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player?
Or is it still difficult for you to accept such leadership?
Germany has not yet got used to it, it is always a bit uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still finding it difficult to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany is positioned as a major player, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and it is that nobody wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
You have to show a receptive attitude to different neighbors and opinions and that's not easy.
The US influence in European politics is declining, but the EU is not filling that void at the moment, so who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to take a more leading role.
Even if they don't like it, if it's disagreeable or if it makes them an even more unpopular town, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly discuss the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
