In the big cities there are large multi-storey warehouses exclusively dedicated to the sale of counterfeits.
However, the Pattloch cases are of a different nature: on behalf of his clients, he is fighting the fact that the trademark office is officially granting Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or the accompanying mark.
The word originates from the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
Chinese authorities feel no guilt
"It's harmful to business, we have to fight it", Pattloch demands.
"The brand is flooding, the monopoly position is disappearing and the damage to the image is enormous".
The financial losses and legal costs of the sectors concerned are in the millions, especially in the case of luxury flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis firm CLSA, with a volume of EUR 15 billion per year, China is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods.
However, it is difficult and expensive to obtain the annulment of registration of dubious legality in the register of trademarks.
The proceedings can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch mentions cases where the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had passed that the name being sued had already become a "market reality".
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged the plagiarist's brand in China", says Pattloch.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
