Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Among the STDs of bacterial origin are syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Snakes and scabies are among the parasitic STDs.
What are the main groups of people affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are more common in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five cases of syphilis in Germany are caused by sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
HIV transmission among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between 15 and 25 years of age.
In our country, the human papillomavirus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How have the numbers of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to compulsory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has doubled from 1,697 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has maintained a downward trend since 2007.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This is one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause genital ulcers, urinary discomfort, flow, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go undetected.
How can one protect oneself?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100 percent protection.
Some pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through dirt and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical examinations, especially if you frequently change sexual partners.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any later consequences can be avoided.
