The astonishing wealth the country enjoys from the oil of the Caspian Sea has not yet reached this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
"Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the celebration of the Eurovision Festival and next year we will celebrate the Festival of the oldest people in the world", says Fatulayeva.
She's the director of the Museum of Longevity, perhaps the only one in the world.
Here is documented the life of eight dozen talyshis of the place who have passed the age of 100 years.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
One of his sons died at the age of 136
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the sheep herder Şirali Müslümov, who seems to have lived to be 168 years old.
However, there is no birth certificate to prove this.
And if we consider that the oldest documented man lived 122 years, it seems that Müslümov's age is quite suspicious.
"She was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973", Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children, and apparently had time to conceive another daughter at the age of 136.
