Norwegian rakfisk - the world's most foul-smelling fish?
Norway's five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has something to do with its greed for a highly smelly fish?
Take a series of overly cured cheeses.
They're in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You will then be able to smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
The scenery is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is allowed to ferment in water for up to a year, depending on how foul-smelling you prefer it to be.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most captivating delicacy, so to speak.
"You eat raw and then drink a glass of aquavit from a drink", says Havard Halvarsen, the city's firefighter who is also known as the "General of Rakfisk", who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking from one sip significant amounts of the drink.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk", says Havard.
The drink can kill the smell.
I'm trying some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it near your nose, that's not bad; it's not much different from a portion of sushi that you've driven a few miles on a bus.
Rakfisk is a product of a very different time, when Norway was in poverty and when, before refrigeration, fish was kept in water and salt in airtight barrels during the autumn.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactive because of alcohol, eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and they emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and even not too long ago much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
The rakfisk is considered an important, essential, though rather foul-smelling, part of Norway's past.
