The Norwegians find it very hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own would be capable of such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway's present wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason we are doing so well", says Anna, our waitress, as she passes rakfisk trays and, with her long blond mane and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, a prudent people".
His English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like to show off".
Norway has managed its oil wealth very carefully; all but a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was squandering money they didn't have in the years leading up to the global financial crisis, Norway kept its wallet tight.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy", says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk", he adds with a wriggly laugh.
I'm in the snow waiting in line for something to eat; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is definitely something different and quite succulent to taste.
But at night, that stinking fish comes back.
The hotel where I stay is one of many places where a rakfisk dinner is held, where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A TV set has connected live with a presenter wearing a bird and surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It's like the Eurovision song contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard". I said, "I'm not going to do it.
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls out of his chair, perhaps beaten by aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes from all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start to his career
As Mexico's incoming President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant discusses the challenges facing the new president and the different expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad these days.
In a city that, at best, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts off several of the main roads leading to the city and is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and assume the management of the nation.
He's faced with a difficult task.
Mexico has been getting good economic results under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is mired in a war against drug trafficking that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has a strong commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence", Mr. Peña Nieto explained earlier this week to U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office.
"I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal".
Before he teamed up with the president of the United States, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his home state of Mexico.
A highly populated and rapidly growing state, surrounding the capital; opinions on the new leader are divided in this territory in which he used to move.
A man of integrity
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
Its residents credit it with the growth of tourism in the area and the construction of infrastructure.
To get to the city, you can drive on one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new roads, which is a huge improvement over the cracked, bumpy roads that were rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques bearing his name at the entrance to a modern sports stadium and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We trust that he will be able to make a real and lasting change", says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, deputy of Mr. Peña Nieto's party, the PRI.
