Hidden beneath highway sections is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called upon to help fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is especially serious.
In a desert plot, next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was governor, a rate far higher than that of Ciudad Juarez, unfortunately famous for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto's critics say, at best, he failed to address the femicide problem while in office.
The most critical accuse his administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to contain her tears while she shows me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
