As her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana watches from the walls, next to a cross that reads one word: Justice.
Yet that's exactly what the family says has been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
What they want is for you to just accept what they say and shut up".
"But that can't be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence", he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will come with a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has promised to give them priority during his term.
"I hope he will be the same kind of president he was when he was governor", says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
Yet that is precisely what the families of the victims of Neza City fear most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors are trying to address allegations of abuse by Bradley Manning during his time in prison.
The trial focuses on Manning's time in Quantico military prison in Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while in military custody.
During the prosecution's interrogation of Manning at a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein claimed that records of weekly visits by unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which was conducted during a hearing following the defense's request that the case be dismissed as his incarceration had been harsh and that it had already involved sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was incarcerated under maximum security from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had described the treatment given to him by the co-ordinators as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional".
The forms show no allegations of ill-treatment, though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concern about some matters and that the officers who visited him had spoken of these problems and had indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record these matters in the record.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after having talked about the problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I would not have mentioned any problems", Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not reported the treatment he was receiving during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said they had put him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below the surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine and (wanted) to stop being on injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life", Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at Marine Corps Base Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that he once fainted from the heat.
He said the fact that he wasn't allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to that cage", Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage".
Manning claimed that once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least 21 hours and often 23 hours, unaccompanied.
Manning said all he was allowed to have was a mattress, a blanket, some flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes while he slept.
He said if the guards couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they'd wake him up so he could turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about the treatment Manning was receiving.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he made in Thursday's statement, according to which, after being forced to sleep naked one night in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the guards and other inmates.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's questioning Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order from the janitor that he should drop the blanket he might have covered himself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he might have used the rubber band on his underwear or his flip-flops to self-harm but that he hadn't.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, his flip-flops, and his glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he went through while in prison and drastically reduce his sentence should he be convicted at the war council, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules that apply to all detainees being held under maximum security at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include collaboration with the enemy, unlawful incitement to publish information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted on all counts, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He says many were forced to leave Mexico because of lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just come down the esplanade and reached the immigration processing area and was already totally confused.
Signs pointed to two lines: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners".
I stood there for a few seconds not sure where to go.
Growing up in Central California, I've been called "Mexican" my whole life.
It's ethnic shorthand, the same way my friends in Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italian".
I decided later on to be Mexican-American.
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was just American.
I speak Spanish well enough to conduct an interview in this language.
But I don't have the level of vocabulary of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and I got in the foreigners' queue.
I thought about that moment this week when the president-elect of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda for the day, as it always is when the leaders of these two countries meet, was: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also keen to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at this time it is as likely that a Mexican will stay in Mexico as it is that he will venture to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a trade bloc in North America like the European Union.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, though he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of its territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them of it are everywhere.
So, the moment a U.S. official says anything that leads to the slightest criticism of Mexico, you start hearing complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how the Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma stand up for war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that's really challenging is the relationship they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans who live in the United States.
Are we talking about a grudge?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, at some point in our family tree, there was a person, maybe a father or a mother or a grandparent, who was shut out of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time, that person fit into a certain profile: dark skin, low education, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not to Mexico.
And, even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight of the fact that what we are living is that, the American dream, not the Mexican dream.
Our identity may not be clear at times, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
We are also aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look over our shoulders as if we were of an inferior class that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't be trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in America but, still, as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came to the United States legally as a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter are upset about it.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel like they're not part of either.
We love to listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of every country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, they see us as Americans.
And in the United States, we're considered Mexicans.
Now, to complicate things further, from what I've learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as makeshift "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would pressure the political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much resentment.
And, with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure that this is a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're gonna be left alone with this idea, fellas.
It's only fair.
If some Mexicans are still not ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated a much shorter time ago.
I'm not sure.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amid the usual futile discussions about who started first, heaps of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed, and for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, even though the Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their ancient conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything in pieces, whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught in the regional upheaval.
Perhaps this will make their fight even bloodier than before.
However, there are reasons to think that their deadly stalemate could be unraveled.
A war that is neither won nor lost
At first glance, optimism seems very difficult to justify at present.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 is maintained, this week's clashes have strengthened the hawks on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has been beaten up.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on the 1.7 million people of Gaza in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to end Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its relentless rivals in Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
Furthermore, Hamas leaders may conclude that time is on their side.
As the Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been Israel's closest Muslim ally, has embraced the cause of Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
The exultant Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is surrounding Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the militia-party Hezbollah dominates, to Syria, where increasingly Islamist-leaning rebels could topple Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, didn't have much time for Hamas.
Instead, the Muslim Brotherhood is Hamas's cousin and its leaders depend more on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, the hard-line Israeli side will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military question is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep more peacefully... for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States is more firm than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
First of all, Israel has prospered, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide terrorists, in part because the barrier corrodes the West Bank, the main piece of territory aspiring to become a Palestinian state, and protects the growing Jewish settlements despite being illegal under international law.
Mr Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even more hard-line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 elections, is in a good position.
Why spoil those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If you really governed the West Bank, wouldn't you fire rockets like your compatriots have in Gaza?
Better to have them behind that wall and give them a good punch if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing will prevail, though the Arab Spring might alter his calculations.
While Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere may not have much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the superpower in the region will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to get the ceasefire is a good omen and could mark the beginning of something.
The Israelis should also think long term.
As the rest of the Arab world becomes more democratic, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination is creating a powder keg that will one day explode in the occupied territories, in the same way that a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and the demographics are making the situation worse as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to repel Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution remains what sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper are advocating: two states and the ceding of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more momentum to the outsiders who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to curb the flow of arms into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented position to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land exchanges and a shared Jerusalem.
The Arab outsiders should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to join.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the impending attempt to obtain virtual state status at the UN.
Mr Obama also has an important role to play in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term he failed to present his own plan for peace.
Back in the White House, he seems just as reluctant to pay attention.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The tobacco packaging law comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and sick parts of the body are displayed on dim-green packets, which are the same for all tobacco brands
The world's first tobacco and generic packaging law is enacted in Australia, replacing the logos and colors of brands with a muted olive green wrapper, gruesome images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and babies who are sick because their parents are smokers.
Apart from the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, which are mandatory from Saturday, are the names of the brands, all printed in a small type of font.
This is the strictest regime in the world for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government says that the goal is to discourage young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make the habit glamorous.
He trusts studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that he will never do so.
"You can see that children, even from a very early age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand", said federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies showing, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies claimed that the law would encourage the black market in tobacco, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
"The legislation will have serious unintended consequences", said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
The amount of tobacco that will be brought in by counterfeiters from China and Indonesia to sell on the streets of Australia will increase.
Others say their business has benefited from the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned business, claimed that the demand for bottle caps and silicone covers to cover the nasty images on the packages had skyrocketed almost from zero two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in the Australian Supreme Court.
Ms. Ha claimed that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale outlets and was expecting more stocks.
"It's a good deal for us".
According to experts, the potential obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector targeted by the plan.
Following a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most retailers to keep cigarettes out of sight, tobacco marketing has moved to online.
Australia has banned internet advertising to local businesses and websites, but cannot restrict it on foreign websites.
"If you're a tobacco marketer and you only have this little window to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be", said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman observed an increase in brand reviews from "common citizens" posted on social networking websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
It is not enough to say that the Commission has not taken the necessary steps to ensure that the Commission's proposals are implemented.
