For four euros, Indonesian volcano porters risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do so, it must descend daily to the bottom of its crater, where sulfur gas emanating from the Earth's interior solidifies upon contact with air.
After plucking large sulphur rocks, which weigh some 70 kilograms in total, he carries them in two bamboo baskets and carries them on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb up the turtle's foot, keeping their balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall off the precipice.
They know that any slip and fall could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago over the cliffs of Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for every kilo of sulfur they mine
Once up, they make their way among tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tirelessly carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1,800 feet [1,850 m].
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better, its workers, who are paid 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for each kilo of sulphur.
Then he sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees [$1,200] each trip", explains Anto, who usually makes three deliveries a day.
He spends three hours on each and ends up crushed, but he is allowed to collect 138,000 rupees (11,5 euros) by the end of the day.
As miserable as it may seem for such an inhuman effort, it's three times what I'd make in the field.
"The miners' pay is very high here, where coffee harvesting is paid at 15,000 rupees (1,2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)", explains the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (€6.2) a day and the cut was not so harsh, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as compelling as sulphur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing and irritation of the eyes by toxic gases
At 27, Anto has been playing the Kawah Ijen for three years, and the sulfur has already started to pay off despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and eye irritation from the toxic gases released by the volcano.
