In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera surcharge that, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance fee, the park guards charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for beasts and not for people", protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old hard-working porter who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades, since leaving school.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilos, she says she will work "as hard as she can" because she needs the money to educate her three children, aged between 18 and 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and drips out the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns coming out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious illnesses - beyond, of course, their usual breathing problems, arthritis, pain in the knees and sores on the shoulders, which have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can now only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to Tamansari's warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat-trail through the bush.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life", proclaims Unainik, opening her mouth wide, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the oldest, aged 30, also works as a sulfur loader.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the world's toughest crafts - that of the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
