But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
The birth rate of Singapore, according to its national population division, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 - known as the replenishment rate - was in 1976.
So why aren't Singaporeans having more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policies at the National Population Division, says it is because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
