While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to keep the small houses from being built.
For example, it has started to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
