However, there are concerns that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate firm EL Developers, says his "shoe boxes" sell out much faster than the larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units sell out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it a lot better for our cash flow.
However, it admits that the new rules give clearer guidance to developers, who were previously hindered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, speaking to Singaporeans working in the financial district of the city centre it seems that they will not have much effect.
"People are under a lot of stress, housing is expensive, and so is education, so many people are putting it off", says one young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But it's important to me to have my own money and time", says another young man in his 20's.
Men and women cite career, stress, and the cost of property and education as reasons for not having children.
So, as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to having babies, Singaporeans have the final say.
Private offline is private online
Privacy, you know.
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is the quality of private or "the sphere of private life that one has the right to protect from any intrusion".
What's private for a 16-year-old?
How do you apply this definition in your daily life and on social media?
Do you understand the dangers you are exposed to by spreading online situations that you would probably not share offline?
The paper interviewed five boys aged 10 to 15 who are frequent net users.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very personal", on a personal level, and "in the password and username", when applied to social networks.
