Or would you like to have a photo of you posted like you posted a friend?
You know what other people post about you?
When you tag party photos, did you ask other people's permission to tag them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing every moment?
Another point is to make them see that they should act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, one acts with respect, morality and other principles, the same should be true on social networks", he says.
The Commission
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and educational consultant, says that it is essential for parents to read the policies of social networks.
By understanding each of these, they have a solid basis for discussing with their children the implications of opening an online account.
"For example, age and what is allowed to share or post", he says.
According to Guardia, it's key to remind children of the lesson of "don't talk to strangers".
UNASUR summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The sixth presidential summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the publicity of the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending leaders.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but sources from the Chancellery and the Presidency pointed out at first that they were going to deliver it after the closure, but later they affirmed that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When consulted on the text, they noted that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Access to the Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, restricted audio".
The little information that circulated among reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the UNASUR governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of assistant presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more data.
Subsequently, the Peruvian Presidency sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is Humala's pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit between South America and the Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite press press pressures, the so-called Lima Declaration was not released.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be confirmed that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure that there were secure transmission systems for all journalists but limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will accept and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today", said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, of the peaceful resolution of controversies, of treaties and of international courts", Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogotá Pact for which it had accepted to submit to the rulings of that international court, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered gravely erroneous.
The summit was held without the assistance of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was responsible for opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The mandate read the final document in which he informed that 16 agreements were adopted and action lines were set for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the residence agreements".
He said that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to low-cost internet in all corners of South America, and to jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and to glimpse a better future for our peoples", added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural areas and borders... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transversal axes of their territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for its reincorporation into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace, and of good neighbourly relations, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his peer from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat in a respectful way the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We will review all these ways, they are not exclusive, including the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega I hope to be able to tell him that we should handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are expected to meet on Saturday in Mexico to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also, as part of the summit, the bloc's Defence Ministers met previously to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
