Fabrizio was 21 years old when he tested positive for AIDS.
"It was like a bomb dropped on me", he says, recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor tried to make "more gentle", without apparent success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inquire about it; with such determination that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients in the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he joined in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options, and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was carrying a cut".
So, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it's possible to survive this syndrome and do so with quality of life.
However, many people, unaware of their illness, still arrive when the virus has already wreaked havoc, "depleting" their immune system, and falling victim to opportunistic infections.
31 years after the first cases of AIDS were reported, "the great achievement means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the HCG, after mentioning that this information was endorsed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of affect on the immune system that patients present at the start of diagnosis, with better expectation for those who are not drug users: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years when they report 500 CD4.
In simple words, this means that those diagnosed with HIV at age 25 "can live without problems until age 75", the interviewee explained.
To gauge this progress, it is worth remembering that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While mortality has fallen significantly in recent years, in Mexico the number of people dying from AIDS dropped from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths until May of this year; however, universal access to antiretroviral drugs has been ensured since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- It seems to me the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I visualize it, that's how it happened in our hospital.
At least for the last 12 years, we haven't had a shortage of medicine. The problem is that patients come in very late because they don't know their infection status, which is late in the disease.
He gave a powerful data: "Nine out of ten patients arrive with some opportunistic infection, and what needs to be done to have a greater impact on global mortality is to make diagnoses earlier and therefore to offer mass screening to all people who need it".
His proposal is agreed by specialists and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (Coesida), as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who went to a particular laboratory to get tested, motivated only because a friend had done it and, despite his young age, he was already in the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know.
"If I'm going to die, I better blow myself up three times a week", they say no to me.
The change was for the better, I eat right, I exercise, I take my medication.
To date, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I am co-responsible, I take care of myself and the other person", said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate with his testimony those who today, in the framework of World AIDS Day, are afraid.
Let them get tested, if they were at risk, the sooner they know they're HIV positive, the better, and if they're diagnosed, let them learn that they can live like anyone else, being responsible.
That, his message, sums up the battle motto for AIDS in 2012.
