In practice, the backlash against the ruling issued on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenseless in the face of the possibility of an embargo on their properties in the Bravo.
However, the resolution opens the door for the leading glass manufacturer in Mexico to go to the United States Supreme Court, alleging three inconsistencies.
For starters, while the trial judge notes that creditors must be governed by the United States Bankruptcy Law, the New Orleans-based Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals says that the main proceeding is the commercial competition in Mexico.
The first point would be to ignore international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases involving transnational companies.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law was created to that end, with the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Second, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, which recognised in the critical mass of the commercial competition the debts which Vitro's subsidiaries had with their parent, the majority required to approve the restructuring would not have been achieved.
