They start a course exploring the "End of the World"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, which many people have held as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: the cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called "Armageddon", and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian end-time theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester there's ever been", Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If you look at what's been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember, bad is good for those of you with the apocalyptic mindset.
And he's not the only professor to teach courses on the "end of the world" this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple, adjunct professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Mediums, Culture, and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time", he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month the students analyzed apocalyptic-themed movies and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
"I've tried to inform students about what's possible, probable, credible and impossible", Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled simply "The End of the World".
"We didn't add '2012' to always have the option of teaching the course again, in case the world doesn't end", Restall said.
Despite the "imminent ruin", students must study, generate projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night the world is supposed to end", Restall said.
The courses proved quite popular.
"It was saturated in two hours", Restall said of his course for high-average students, which was filled with 35 students.
We've been getting e-mails for weeks and weeks before the semester starts, from people asking if there's still room.
The students, on the other hand, say that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves", said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old graduate student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden.
And the point is that the apocalyptic mindset, secular or religious, is just a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing graduate student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I had never heard of a class that could teach that", he said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed - much less a teacher - said he believed in the expiration date of December 21.
"Our first project was about the Mayan prophecy and we kind of discredited it", said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple and from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, going back several centuries, where people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom in these speculations.
"Other places people don't think about this", he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching courses in the Philippines this year, quickly responded to the question of whether he knew of any course on the "end of the world" there.
"The Philippines is not involved in the end of the world", he wrote, implying an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that many doomsday days have been talked about over the years, and he said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they were thinking of going to "end of the world" parties.
"Maybe I'll call some friends and we'll have a laugh together", said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
